<Layout title="The New Horizons Mission" description="NASA's New Horizons spacecraft and its 2015 flyby of Pluto.">
  <h1>New Horizons: The Pluto Flyby</h1>
  <p>
    New Horizons is the only spacecraft ever to visit Pluto. Launched on
    19 January 2006 — months before Pluto was reclassified as a dwarf planet —
    it raced across the Solar System and made its closest approach on
    14 July 2015.
  </p>

  <!-- Spacecraft image deliberately missing alt (image-alt) -->
  <figure>
    <img src="/images/new-horizons-spacecraft.png" width="360" class="content-img" />
    <figcaption>NASA's piano-sized New Horizons spacecraft.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>The fastest spacecraft ever launched</h2>
  <p>
    New Horizons left Earth at about 16 km/s, the fastest launch speed of any
    spacecraft. Even so, the journey to Pluto took nine and a half years. It flew
    just 12,500 km above Pluto's surface, gathering more data in a few hours than
    decades of telescope observation had produced.
  </p>

  <!-- Low-contrast statistic figures (color-contrast) -->
  <p>
    <span class="muted-fail" style="font-size:1.4rem;font-weight:700;">9.5 years</span>
    <span class="muted-fail"> travel time &nbsp;•&nbsp; </span>
    <span class="muted-fail" style="font-size:1.4rem;font-weight:700;">12,500 km</span>
    <span class="muted-fail"> closest approach &nbsp;•&nbsp; </span>
    <span class="muted-fail" style="font-size:1.4rem;font-weight:700;">5 billion km</span>
    <span class="muted-fail"> from home</span>
  </p>

  <h2>What it carried</h2>
  <!-- Disclosure button with an INVALID aria-expanded value (aria-valid-attr-value).
       Valid values are "true" or "false", not "open". -->
  <button type="button" aria-expanded="open" aria-controls="instrument-list">
    Show the science instruments
  </button>
  <ul id="instrument-list">
    <li><strong>Ralph</strong> — colour and infrared imaging and spectroscopy.</li>
    <li><strong>Alice</strong> — ultraviolet spectrometer to study the atmosphere.</li>
    <li><strong>LORRI</strong> — a long-range telescopic camera for sharp images.</li>
    <li><strong>REX, SWAP, PEPSSI, SDC</strong> — radio science, solar wind, and dust instruments.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Onward into the Kuiper Belt</h2>
  <p>
    After Pluto, New Horizons kept going. On 1 January 2019 it flew past a small,
    two-lobed Kuiper Belt object now named Arrokoth — the most distant object
    ever explored up close. The spacecraft is still operating and sending data
    as it heads out of the Solar System.
  </p>
</Layout>
